==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧lt)</pr>, <def><pos>3d pers. sing. pres.</pos>
of <er>Hold</er>, contraction for <xex>holdeth</xex>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧lt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly
<ets>alt</ets>, It. <ets>alto</ets>, G. <ets>halt</ets>, fr.
<ets>halten</ets> to hold. See <er>Hold</er>.]</ety> <def>A stop in
marching or walking, or in any action; arrest of progress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without any <qex>halt</qex> they marched.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Lovers] soon in passion's war contest,⟦br⟧
Yet in their march soon make a <qex>halt</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Davenant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Halted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Halting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hold one's self
from proceeding; to hold up; to cease progress; to stop for a longer or
shorter period; to come to a stop; to stand still.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stand in doubt whether to proceed, or what to do;
to hesitate; to be uncertain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How long <qex>halt</qex> ye between two opinions?</q> <rj><qau>1
Kings xviii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧lt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>
<def>To cause to cease marching; to stop; <as>as, the general
<ex>halted</ex> his troops for refreshment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>healt</ets>; akin to OS.,
Dan., & Sw. <ets>halt</ets>, Icel. <ets>haltr</ets>, <ets>halltr</ets>,
Goth. <ets>halts</ets>, OHG. <ets>halz</ets>.]</ety> <def>Halting or
stopping in walking; lame.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring in hither the poor, and the maimed, and the <qex>halt</qex>,
and the blind.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xiv. 21. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of limping;
lameness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Halt
<hw>Halt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>halten</ets>, AS.
<ets>healtian</ets>. See <er>Halt</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk lamely; to limp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have an irregular rhythm; to be
defective.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blank verse shall <qex>halt</qex> for it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halter</ent>⟦br⟧
